The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Smooth take-off for airport project
                                                                                                               Smooth take-off for airport project
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, July 31: Bengal Aerotropolis Projects Ltd (BAPL)  the private operator which is developing an airport at Andal in Burdwan  has secured 320 acres within the first 10 days of compensation distribution.        
	The district administration has begun offering cheques to the land givers from July 20 for 550 acres.         
	BAPL needs 2,181 acres in the first phase of the airport city project.        
	The cheque distribution process is going on well. As of yesterday, compensation for 666 plots has been given, Subroto Paul, chief executive officer of BAPL, said.        
	The company expects the acquisition to be over by the end of this year. Changi Airport of Singapore owns 26 per cent in BAPL.        
	The firm has signed an MoU with the state technical education and training department to impart vocational training to the land givers.        
	BAPL will offer technical education through ITI Durgapur to about 5,000 individuals from the families affected by the project. It will also upgrade the ITI classrooms and build workshops.        
	BAPL vice-president Kaushik Banerjee said the company would keep a record of those receiving training. There will be many projects in Aerotropolis health and IT city. When developers would look for skilled professionals, we will suggest these names, he said.                                                                                                                                        
